-- China Stocks: Aluminum Corp. of China, Citic Securities, ICBC
-- B y   W e i y i   L i m
-- 2012-04-05T07:48:44Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-04-05/china-stocks-aluminum-corp-of-china-citic-securities-icbc.html
Shares of the following companies
had  unusual  moves in  China  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses as of the close.  The  Shanghai Composite Index (SHCOMP) , which tracks the bigger of
China’s stock exchanges, rose 39.45 points, or 1.7 percent, the
most since Feb. 8. The  CSI 300 Index (SHSZ300)  climbed 2.4 percent to
2,512.83.  Aluminum Corp. of China Ltd.  (601600 CH), the biggest
Chinese producer of the metal, added 3.7 percent to 6.81 yuan,
the most since March 21. The 21st Century Business Herald said
its parent company plans to boost investment in rare earth
production in Guangxi province.  Citic Securities Co. (600030)  (600030 CH), the biggest-listed
brokerage, jumped 5.8 percent to 12.26 yuan.   Haitong Securities
Co. (600837)  (600837 CH) rose 7.8 percent to 9.71 yuan.  The China Securities Regulatory Commission increased quotas
for qualified foreign institutional investors to $80 billion
from $30 billion.  Industrial & Commercial Bank of China Ltd.  (601398 CH), the
biggest lender, slid 0.7 percent to 4.30 yuan, while largest
rival  China Construction Bank Corp. (601939)  (601939 CH) declined 0.8
percent to 4.79 yuan.  China needs to break a banking “monopoly” of a few big
lenders that make easy profits because it’s hard to borrow money
elsewhere, Wen said. Earnings at China’s biggest banks are
growing even as a cooling economy triggers loan defaults.  To contact the reporter on this story:
